orted Western CDs still play most of the tracks. They also played a crucial role in the emergence of the new music and youth culture. De Kloet's impressive study demonstrates how the young Chinese cope with the rapid economic and social changes in a period of intense globalisation, and offers a unique insight into the socio-cultural and political transformations of a rising global power.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aMusic audienceszChinaxHistoryy20th century. 0aMusic tradezChinaxHistoryy20th century. 0aMusiczChinay20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 4aAsian Studies. 4aCUL. 4aCultural Studies. 7aMUSIC / Ethnomusicology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAUP eBook Package Backfile 2000-2013z978311070067140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9789048511143zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789048511143423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9789048511143.jpg  a978-3-11-070067-1  AUP eBook Package Backfile 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK